<div class="lang-en">
<section id="what-is">
      <h2>What Is Traditional Chinese Medicine?</h2>
      <p>Traditional Chinese Medicine (<span class="chinese-char">中醫</span>, Zhōngyī) is a comprehensive system of healthcare that has evolved continuously for over 2,500 years. Far from being a single practice, TCM encompasses <strong>acupuncture</strong>, <strong>herbal medicine</strong> (comprising thousands of medicinal substances), <strong>tui na</strong> (therapeutic massage), <strong>dietary therapy</strong>, and <strong>qigong</strong> (breathing and movement exercises).</p>
      <p>All branches of TCM share a unified theoretical framework grounded in three pillars: the flow of <em>qi</em> (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>), the dynamic balance of <em>yin and yang</em> (<span class="chinese-char">陰陽</span>), and the <a href="/wuxing/">five element correspondences</a> (<span class="chinese-char">五行</span>). Disease, in the TCM view, is not an invading entity to be destroyed but a loss of internal balance to be restored.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="foundations">
      <h2>The Huangdi Neijing &mdash; Foundational Text</h2>
      <p>The <em>Huangdi Neijing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">黃帝內經</span>, Yellow Emperor's Classic of Internal Medicine) is the founding text of Chinese medicine. Compiled during the late Warring States to early Han Dynasty period (c. 300 BCE &ndash; 100 CE), it takes the form of a dialogue between the Yellow Emperor and his physician Qi Bo.</p>
      <p>The text consists of two parts: the <em>Suwen</em> (<span class="chinese-char">素問</span>, Basic Questions) covering medical theory, and the <em>Lingshu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">靈樞</span>, Spiritual Pivot) detailing acupuncture and meridian theory. Together, they establish the diagnostic principles, treatment strategies, and preventive philosophy that remain central to TCM practice today.</p>
      <p>Other seminal texts include the <em>Shennong Bencao Jing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">神農本草經</span>, c. 200 CE) cataloguing 365 medicinal substances, and Zhang Zhongjing's <em>Shanghan Lun</em> (<span class="chinese-char">傷寒論</span>, c. 220 CE), which remains the most clinically influential herbal medicine text in history.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="qi">
      <h2>Qi &mdash; Vital Energy</h2>
      <p>Qi (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>) is the fundamental concept in Chinese medicine. It refers to the vital energy that animates all living things and circulates through the body along defined pathways called <strong>meridians</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">經絡</span>, jīngluò). Health is maintained when qi flows freely and abundantly; disease arises when qi becomes blocked, deficient, or stagnant.</p>
      <p>TCM recognises several types of qi:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Yuan Qi (<span class="chinese-char">元氣</span>)</strong> &mdash; Original qi, inherited from parents, stored in the kidneys</li>
        <li><strong>Gu Qi (<span class="chinese-char">穀氣</span>)</strong> &mdash; Grain qi, derived from food and drink through the spleen and stomach</li>
        <li><strong>Zong Qi (<span class="chinese-char">宗氣</span>)</strong> &mdash; Gathering qi, formed in the chest from the combination of air and food qi</li>
        <li><strong>Wei Qi (<span class="chinese-char">衛氣</span>)</strong> &mdash; Defensive qi, circulating at the body's surface to protect against external pathogens</li>
        <li><strong>Ying Qi (<span class="chinese-char">營氣</span>)</strong> &mdash; Nutritive qi, flowing within the meridians to nourish organs and tissues</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="zangfu">
      <h2>Zang-Fu Organ Theory</h2>
      <p>TCM organises the body's internal organs into two groups based on <a href="/wuxing/">five element</a> correspondences:</p>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Element</th><th>Zang (Yin Organ)</th><th>Fu (Yang Organ)</th><th>Emotion</th><th>Sense</th><th>Tissue</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Wood</td><td>Liver (<span class="chinese-char">肝</span>)</td><td>Gallbladder (<span class="chinese-char">膽</span>)</td><td>Anger</td><td>Eyes</td><td>Sinews</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fire</td><td>Heart (<span class="chinese-char">心</span>)</td><td>Small Intestine (<span class="chinese-char">小腸</span>)</td><td>Joy</td><td>Tongue</td><td>Blood Vessels</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Earth</td><td>Spleen (<span class="chinese-char">脾</span>)</td><td>Stomach (<span class="chinese-char">胃</span>)</td><td>Worry</td><td>Mouth</td><td>Muscles</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Metal</td><td>Lungs (<span class="chinese-char">肺</span>)</td><td>Large Intestine (<span class="chinese-char">大腸</span>)</td><td>Grief</td><td>Nose</td><td>Skin</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Water</td><td>Kidneys (<span class="chinese-char">腎</span>)</td><td>Bladder (<span class="chinese-char">膀胱</span>)</td><td>Fear</td><td>Ears</td><td>Bones</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>It is essential to understand that TCM organs are <em>functional systems</em>, not strictly anatomical structures. The TCM "Spleen," for example, encompasses digestive transformation and transport of nutrients &mdash; functions that Western medicine distributes across multiple organs. The five <em>zang</em> organs store vital substances; the six <em>fu</em> organs (including the Triple Burner, <span class="chinese-char">三焦</span>) transform and transport.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="meridians">
      <h2>Meridians and Acupuncture</h2>
      <p>The meridian system (<span class="chinese-char">經絡</span>) consists of 12 primary channels connecting the internal organs to the body's surface, plus eight extraordinary vessels. Along these channels lie <strong>361 classical acupuncture points</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">穴位</span>), each with specific therapeutic actions.</p>
      <p>Acupuncture (<span class="chinese-char">針灸</span>, zhēnjiǔ) involves inserting fine needles at selected points to regulate qi flow, clear blockages, and restore yin-yang balance. The <em>Lingshu</em> details needling techniques including tonification (to strengthen deficiency), sedation (to clear excess), and various manipulation methods that affect the direction and quality of qi movement.</p>
      <p>Moxibustion (<span class="chinese-char">灸</span>, jiǔ) &mdash; the burning of dried mugwort (Artemisia vulgaris) at or near acupuncture points &mdash; is the thermal complement to needling, used particularly for cold and deficiency patterns.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal">
      <h2>Herbal Medicine</h2>
      <p>Chinese herbal medicine (<span class="chinese-char">中藥</span>, zhōngyào) is the most widely used branch of TCM. The classical pharmacopoeia includes over 5,000 substances &mdash; primarily plants, but also minerals and animal products. Herbs are classified by their temperature (hot, warm, cool, cold), taste (sour, bitter, sweet, pungent, salty), and the meridians they enter.</p>
      <p>Prescriptions (<span class="chinese-char">方劑</span>) typically combine multiple herbs following a structural logic:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Jun (<span class="chinese-char">君</span>) &mdash; Emperor</strong>: The primary herb targeting the main condition</li>
        <li><strong>Chen (<span class="chinese-char">臣</span>) &mdash; Minister</strong>: Supports the emperor herb's action</li>
        <li><strong>Zuo (<span class="chinese-char">佐</span>) &mdash; Assistant</strong>: Addresses secondary symptoms or moderates harsh effects</li>
        <li><strong>Shi (<span class="chinese-char">使</span>) &mdash; Guide</strong>: Directs the formula to specific meridians or harmonises the combination</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal-medicine-detail">
      <h2>Classical Herbal Traditions (<span class="chinese-char">中草藥</span>, <span class="pinyin">Zhōngcǎoyào</span>)</h2>
      <p>Chinese herbal medicine reached its greatest pre-modern synthesis in the <strong>Ming Dynasty</strong> masterwork <em>Bencao Gangmu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">本草綱目</span>, <span class="pinyin">Běncǎo Gāngmù</span>, "Compendium of Materia Medica"), completed by <strong>Li Shizhen</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">李時珍</span>) in 1578 after 27 years of research. This encyclopaedia catalogued <strong>1,892 medicinal substances</strong> with 11,096 prescriptions, organised by a classification system that anticipated modern taxonomy.</p>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>Li Shizhen personally tested many substances, travelled to remote mountain regions to collect specimens, and critically evaluated centuries of accumulated medical literature. He corrected numerous errors in earlier texts and rejected superstitious claims, applying empirical observation that was remarkable for his era.</p>
        <cite>— Li Shizhen, <em>《本草綱目》</em>, Ming Dynasty (1578)</cite>
      </div>
      <p>Earlier landmark texts include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><em>Shennong Bencao Jing</em></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">神農本草經</span>, c. 200 CE) — The first materia medica, classifying 365 substances into three grades (upper, middle, lower) based on toxicity and therapeutic value</li>
        <li><strong><em>Shanghan Lun</em></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">傷寒論</span>, c. 220 CE) by Zhang Zhongjing — Clinical herbal prescriptions for acute febrile diseases, still used in practice today</li>
        <li><strong><em>Qianjin Yaofang</em></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">千金要方</span>, 652 CE) by Sun Simiao (<span class="chinese-char">孫思邈</span>) — Tang Dynasty encyclopaedia integrating herbal medicine with dietary therapy and preventive care</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="food-therapy">
      <h2>Food Therapy (<span class="chinese-char">食療</span>, <span class="pinyin">Shíliáo</span>)</h2>
      <p>The principle <strong>"medicine and food share the same origin"</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">藥食同源</span>, <span class="pinyin">yàoshí tóngyuán</span>) is fundamental to Chinese medical thinking. The <em>Huangdi Neijing</em> states: "When treating disease, use medicine only when diet fails." Food therapy uses everyday ingredients classified by their thermal nature (hot, warm, neutral, cool, cold) and flavour to prevent disease and support recovery.</p>

      <h3>Cantonese Food Therapy (<span class="chinese-char">廣式食療</span>)</h3>
      <p>Guangdong province developed the most sophisticated food therapy tradition in China, driven by the subtropical climate's demand for heat-clearing and dampness-draining foods. <strong>Cantonese slow-cooked soups</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">老火湯</span>, <span class="pinyin">lǎohuǒ tāng</span>) are the most recognisable expression — simmered for 3–6 hours to extract the medicinal properties of ingredients like:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">淮山</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">huáishān</span>, Chinese yam) — strengthens spleen qi, benefits kidneys</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">蓮子</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">liánzǐ</span>, lotus seed) — calms the heart, stops diarrhoea</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">杞子</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">qǐzǐ</span>, goji berry) — nourishes liver and kidney yin, brightens the eyes</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">紅棗</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">hóngzǎo</span>, red date) — tonifies qi and blood, harmonises other herbs</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">陳皮</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">chénpí</span>, aged tangerine peel) — regulates qi, dries dampness, aids digestion</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In Cantonese households, the daily soup selection follows a seasonal logic: cooling soups (<span class="chinese-char">清熱湯</span>) in summer, warming and nourishing soups (<span class="chinese-char">補湯</span>) in winter, dampness-draining soups during the humid spring monsoon season. This is food therapy practised at a civilisational scale.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal-tea">
      <h2>Cantonese Herbal Tea (<span class="chinese-char">涼茶</span>, <span class="pinyin">Liángchá</span>)</h2>
      <p><strong>Liangcha</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">涼茶</span>, literally "cooling tea") is a Guangdong tradition of herbal beverages brewed to counteract the region's hot, humid climate. Despite the name, liangcha is not tea (<em>Camellia sinensis</em>) but rather medicinal herbal infusions, sometimes bitter, consumed for preventive health maintenance.</p>
      <p>Common liangcha formulas include:</p>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Name</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Key Herbs</th><th>Function</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Wanglaoji</td><td><span class="chinese-char">王老吉</span></td><td>Mesona, chrysanthemum, honeysuckle</td><td>General heat-clearing, sore throat</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Ershisi Wei</td><td><span class="chinese-char">廿四味</span></td><td>24 herbs (varies by shop)</td><td>Heavy-duty heat-clearing, detoxification</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Luohanguo Tea</td><td><span class="chinese-char">羅漢果茶</span></td><td>Monk fruit, chrysanthemum</td><td>Cough relief, lung moisture</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Jigucao Tea</td><td><span class="chinese-char">雞骨草茶</span></td><td>Abrus herb, dates</td><td>Liver protection, dampness drainage</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Cantonese herbal tea shops (<span class="chinese-char">涼茶鋪</span>) have been a feature of Guangdong street life for centuries. The tradition was inscribed on China's national intangible cultural heritage list in 2006, recognising its deep roots in southern Chinese medical culture.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="diagnosis">
      <h2>Diagnostic Methods</h2>
      <p>TCM diagnosis relies on four examinations (<span class="chinese-char">四診</span>):</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Observation (<span class="chinese-char">望</span>)</strong> &mdash; Examining the face, tongue, complexion, body type, and demeanour. Tongue diagnosis is particularly refined, with the tongue's colour, coating, shape, and moisture reflecting internal conditions.</li>
        <li><strong>Listening and Smelling (<span class="chinese-char">聞</span>)</strong> &mdash; Assessing the quality of voice, breath, cough, and body odour</li>
        <li><strong>Inquiry (<span class="chinese-char">問</span>)</strong> &mdash; Systematic questioning about symptoms, sleep, appetite, digestion, temperature sensitivity, emotional state, and medical history</li>
        <li><strong>Palpation (<span class="chinese-char">切</span>)</strong> &mdash; Pulse diagnosis at the radial artery, where the practitioner identifies up to 28 distinct pulse qualities across three positions on each wrist, each reflecting different organ systems</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="connection">
      <h2>TCM and Chinese Metaphysics</h2>
      <p>Traditional Chinese Medicine shares its theoretical DNA with the other arts of Chinese metaphysics. The same <a href="/wuxing/">five element theory</a> that governs medical diagnosis also structures <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> chart reading, <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a> spatial analysis, and <a href="/qimen/">Qi Men Dun Jia</a> temporal divination. The <a href="/calendar/">Chinese calendar</a>'s Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches are used in TCM to identify the cosmic influences affecting health at any given time.</p>
      <p>This interconnection is not coincidental &mdash; it reflects the Chinese cosmological view that the human body is a microcosm of the universe, subject to the same principles that govern the natural world. A skilled practitioner reads the body much as a feng shui master reads a landscape: looking for harmony, flow, and balance among the elemental forces.</p>
    </section>
</div>

<div class="lang-tc">
<section id="what-is">
      <h2>何謂中醫？</h2>
      <p>中醫（<span class="chinese-char">中醫</span>，Zhōngyī）是一套持續發展逾兩千五百年的完整醫療體系。中醫絕非單一療法，而是涵蓋<strong>針灸</strong>、<strong>中藥</strong>（包含數千種藥用物質）、<strong>推拿</strong>（治療性手法）、<strong>食療</strong>以及<strong>氣功</strong>（呼吸導引與運動功法）的綜合醫學。</p>
      <p>中醫各分支共享統一的理論框架，建基於三大支柱：<em>氣</em>（<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>）的運行、<em>陰陽</em>（<span class="chinese-char">陰陽</span>）的動態平衡，以及<a href="/wuxing/">五行對應關係</a>（<span class="chinese-char">五行</span>）。在中醫觀念中，疾病並非有待消滅的入侵之敵，而是需要恢復的內在平衡失調。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="foundations">
      <h2>《黃帝內經》&mdash; 奠基之作</h2>
      <p>《<em>黃帝內經</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">黃帝內經</span>，Yellow Emperor's Classic of Internal Medicine）是中醫學的奠基經典。成書於戰國末期至西漢初年（約公元前300年 &ndash; 公元100年），以黃帝與其御醫岐伯問答的形式撰寫。</p>
      <p>全書分為兩部分：《<em>素問</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">素問</span>，基礎理論問答）論述醫學原理，《<em>靈樞</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">靈樞</span>，針灸總論）詳述針灸與經絡理論。兩者共同奠定了診斷原則、治療策略與預防思想，至今仍為中醫臨床實踐之核心。</p>
      <p>其他重要典籍包括：《<em>神農本草經</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">神農本草經</span>，約公元200年）收錄365種藥物，以及張仲景所著《<em>傷寒論</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">傷寒論</span>，約公元220年），後者堪稱中醫史上臨床影響最為深遠的方書。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="qi">
      <h2>氣 &mdash; 生命之能</h2>
      <p>氣（<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>）是中醫最根本的概念。氣指維繫一切生命活動的vital能量，沿著稱為<strong>經絡</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">經絡</span>，jīngluò）的特定通路在體內循行。氣行通暢、充盈則身體健康；氣滯、氣虛或氣阻則百病叢生。</p>
      <p>中醫區分數種氣的類型：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>元氣（<span class="chinese-char">元氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 先天之氣，稟受於父母，藏於腎臟</li>
        <li><strong>穀氣（<span class="chinese-char">穀氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 水穀之氣，經脾胃運化飲食而生</li>
        <li><strong>宗氣（<span class="chinese-char">宗氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 聚於胸中，由天氣與穀氣結合而成</li>
        <li><strong>衛氣（<span class="chinese-char">衛氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 護衛之氣，行於體表，抵禦外邪</li>
        <li><strong>營氣（<span class="chinese-char">營氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 營養之氣，行於經脈之中，濡養臟腑組織</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="zangfu">
      <h2>臟腑理論</h2>
      <p>中醫依據<a href="/wuxing/">五行</a>對應關係，將人體內臟分為兩組：</p>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>五行</th><th>臟（陰臟）</th><th>腑（陽腑）</th><th>情志</th><th>五官</th><th>主體</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>木</td><td>肝（<span class="chinese-char">肝</span>）</td><td>膽（<span class="chinese-char">膽</span>）</td><td>怒</td><td>目</td><td>筋</td></tr>
          <tr><td>火</td><td>心（<span class="chinese-char">心</span>）</td><td>小腸（<span class="chinese-char">小腸</span>）</td><td>喜</td><td>舌</td><td>脈</td></tr>
          <tr><td>土</td><td>脾（<span class="chinese-char">脾</span>）</td><td>胃（<span class="chinese-char">胃</span>）</td><td>思</td><td>口</td><td>肌肉</td></tr>
          <tr><td>金</td><td>肺（<span class="chinese-char">肺</span>）</td><td>大腸（<span class="chinese-char">大腸</span>）</td><td>悲</td><td>鼻</td><td>皮毛</td></tr>
          <tr><td>水</td><td>腎（<span class="chinese-char">腎</span>）</td><td>膀胱（<span class="chinese-char">膀胱</span>）</td><td>恐</td><td>耳</td><td>骨</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>必須理解，中醫所言之臟腑乃<em>功能系統</em>，而非純粹的解剖結構。例如中醫之「脾」，涵蓋消化運化與營養輸布等功能 &mdash; 此等功能在西方醫學中分屬多個器官。五臟貯藏精微物質；六腑（包括三焦，<span class="chinese-char">三焦</span>）主轉化輸運。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="meridians">
      <h2>經絡與針灸</h2>
      <p>經絡系統（<span class="chinese-char">經絡</span>）由十二正經構成，連通內臟與體表，另有奇經八脈。經絡之上分佈著<strong>三百六十一個經典穴位</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">穴位</span>），各具特定治療功效。</p>
      <p>針灸（<span class="chinese-char">針灸</span>，zhēnjiǔ）是在選定穴位施以細針，以調節氣的運行、疏通阻滯、恢復陰陽平衡。《<em>靈樞</em>》詳載補法（針對虛證）、瀉法（針對實證）等針法技巧，以及影響氣行方向與性質的各種手法。</p>
      <p>灸法（<span class="chinese-char">灸</span>，jiǔ）&mdash; 將乾燥艾草（Artemisia vulgaris）置於穴位之上或附近燃燒 &mdash; 是針法的溫熱互補療法，尤適用於寒證與虛證。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal">
      <h2>中藥方劑</h2>
      <p>中藥（<span class="chinese-char">中藥</span>，zhōngyào）是中醫最廣泛應用的分支。經典本草收錄逾五千種藥物 &mdash; 以植物為主，兼含礦物及動物類藥材。藥物依其性味分類：四氣（熱、溫、涼、寒）、五味（酸、苦、甘、辛、鹹），以及歸經。</p>
      <p>方劑（<span class="chinese-char">方劑</span>）通常遵循嚴謹的組方邏輯配伍多味藥材：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>君（<span class="chinese-char">君</span>）&mdash; 君藥</strong>：針對主證的核心藥物</li>
        <li><strong>臣（<span class="chinese-char">臣</span>）&mdash; 臣藥</strong>：輔佐君藥之功效</li>
        <li><strong>佐（<span class="chinese-char">佐</span>）&mdash; 佐藥</strong>：兼治次要症狀或緩和峻烈之性</li>
        <li><strong>使（<span class="chinese-char">使</span>）&mdash; 使藥</strong>：引經報使或調和諸藥</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal-medicine-detail">
      <h2>經典本草傳統（<span class="chinese-char">中草藥</span>，<span class="pinyin">Zhōngcǎoyào</span>）</h2>
      <p>中草藥學在<strong>明代</strong>巨著《<em>本草綱目</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">本草綱目</span>，<span class="pinyin">Běncǎo Gāngmù</span>）中達到了前近代的最高綜合。此書由<strong>李時珍</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">李時珍</span>）歷經二十七年研究，於1578年完成。全書收錄<strong>一千八百九十二種藥物</strong>，附方一萬一千零九十六首，其分類體系之精密，已預示了現代分類學的思路。</p>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>李時珍親嘗眾藥，跋涉深山採集標本，並嚴謹審視歷代醫藥文獻。他訂正了前人著述中的大量錯誤，摒棄迷信之說，其實證精神在當時的時代背景下實屬非凡。</p>
        <cite>— 李時珍，<em>《本草綱目》</em>，明代（1578年）</cite>
      </div>
      <p>更早的里程碑著作包括：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><em>《神農本草經》</em></strong>（<span class="chinese-char">神農本草經</span>，約公元200年）— 第一部本草專著，將365種藥物按毒性與療效分為上、中、下三品</li>
        <li><strong><em>《傷寒論》</em></strong>（<span class="chinese-char">傷寒論</span>，約公元220年），張仲景著 — 外感熱病的經方著作，至今仍廣泛應用於臨床</li>
        <li><strong><em>《千金要方》</em></strong>（<span class="chinese-char">千金要方</span>，652年），孫思邈（<span class="chinese-char">孫思邈</span>）著 — 唐代醫學百科，融合中藥、食療與養生保健</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="food-therapy">
      <h2>食療（<span class="chinese-char">食療</span>，<span class="pinyin">Shíliáo</span>）</h2>
      <p><strong>「藥食同源」</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">藥食同源</span>，<span class="pinyin">yàoshí tóngyuán</span>）是中醫學的根本理念。《<em>黃帝內經</em>》有云：「治病先以食療，食之不愈，然後用藥。」食療運用日常食材，依其性味（熱、溫、平、涼、寒）與味道分類，以防病養生、輔助康復。</p>

      <h3>廣式食療（<span class="chinese-char">廣式食療</span>）</h3>
      <p>廣東發展出中國最為精緻的食療傳統，此與嶺南亞熱帶氣候對清熱祛濕食物的需求密不可分。<strong>廣東老火湯</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">老火湯</span>，<span class="pinyin">lǎohuǒ tāng</span>）是最具代表性的食療形式 — 以文火慢燉三至六小時，以充分萃取藥材功效，常用材料包括：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">淮山</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">huáishān</span>，山藥）— 健脾益氣，補腎固精</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">蓮子</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">liánzǐ</span>，蓮子）— 養心安神，澀腸止瀉</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">杞子</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">qǐzǐ</span>，枸杞）— 滋補肝腎，明目益精</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">紅棗</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">hóngzǎo</span>，紅棗）— 補中益氣，養血調和</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">陳皮</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">chénpí</span>，陳皮）— 理氣燥濕，健脾助消化</li>
      </ul>
      <p>在廣東家庭中，每日煲湯遵循時令邏輯：夏飲清熱湯（<span class="chinese-char">清熱湯</span>），冬進溫補湯（<span class="chinese-char">補湯</span>），春季潮濕回南天則煲祛濕湯。此乃文明尺度上的食療實踐。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal-tea">
      <h2>廣東涼茶（<span class="chinese-char">涼茶</span>，<span class="pinyin">Liángchá</span>）</h2>
      <p><strong>涼茶</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">涼茶</span>，字面意為「清涼之茶」）是廣東地區以草藥煎煮飲品來對抗炎熱潮濕氣候的傳統。涼茶並非真正的茶葉（<em>Camellia sinensis</em>），而是帶有藥用功效的草本飲料，味道有時偏苦，用於日常保健。</p>
      <p>常見的涼茶配方包括：</p>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>名稱</th><th>中文</th><th>主要藥材</th><th>功效</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>王老吉</td><td><span class="chinese-char">王老吉</span></td><td>仙草、菊花、金銀花</td><td>清熱解毒，利咽消腫</td></tr>
          <tr><td>廿四味</td><td><span class="chinese-char">廿四味</span></td><td>二十四味藥材（各店配方不同）</td><td>重度清熱，解毒祛邪</td></tr>
          <tr><td>羅漢果茶</td><td><span class="chinese-char">羅漢果茶</span></td><td>羅漢果、菊花</td><td>止咳潤肺</td></tr>
          <tr><td>雞骨草茶</td><td><span class="chinese-char">雞骨草茶</span></td><td>雞骨草、紅棗</td><td>護肝利膽，清熱祛濕</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>涼茶鋪（<span class="chinese-char">涼茶鋪</span>）數百年來一直是廣東街頭的獨特風景。2006年，涼茶文化被列入中國國家級非物質文化遺產名錄，彰顯其在嶺南醫藥文化中的深厚根基。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="diagnosis">
      <h2>診斷方法</h2>
      <p>中醫診斷依賴四診合參（<span class="chinese-char">四診</span>）：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>望診（<span class="chinese-char">望</span>）</strong> &mdash; 觀察面色、舌象、膚色、體型與神態。舌診尤為精細，舌的顏色、苔質、形態與潤燥皆反映體內狀況。</li>
        <li><strong>聞診（<span class="chinese-char">聞</span>）</strong> &mdash; 聽辨聲音、呼吸、咳嗽之質，嗅察體氣</li>
        <li><strong>問診（<span class="chinese-char">問</span>）</strong> &mdash; 系統詢問症狀、睡眠、食慾、消化、寒熱偏向、情志狀態及病史</li>
        <li><strong>切診（<span class="chinese-char">切</span>）</strong> &mdash; 於寸口橈動脈處行脈診，醫者可辨二十八種脈象，分佈三部九候，各對應不同臟腑系統</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="connection">
      <h2>中醫與中國玄學</h2>
      <p>中醫與中國玄學諸術共享相同的理論基因。用於醫學診斷的<a href="/wuxing/">五行學說</a>，同樣構成<a href="/bazi/">八字</a>命理分析、<a href="/fengshui/">風水</a>空間研判及<a href="/qimen/">奇門遁甲</a>時空預測的基本架構。<a href="/calendar/">中國曆法</a>中的天干地支亦用於中醫，以判斷特定時間對人體健康的宇宙影響。</p>
      <p>此種互通並非偶然 &mdash; 它體現了中國宇宙觀中「人身即天地之縮影」的核心思想，人體與自然界遵循同一法則。高明的醫者診察人體，恰如風水名家堪輿山川：皆在五行之間尋求和諧、通暢與平衡。</p>
    </section>
</div>

<div class="lang-sc">
<section id="what-is">
      <h2>何谓中医？</h2>
      <p>中医（<span class="chinese-char">中醫</span>，Zhōngyī）是一套持续发展逾两千五百年的完整医疗体系。中医绝非单一疗法，而是涵盖<strong>针灸</strong>、<strong>中药</strong>（包含数千种药用物质）、<strong>推拿</strong>（治疗性手法）、<strong>食疗</strong>以及<strong>气功</strong>（呼吸导引与运动功法）的综合医学。</p>
      <p>中医各分支共享统一的理论框架，建基于三大支柱：<em>气</em>（<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>）的运行、<em>阴阳</em>（<span class="chinese-char">陰陽</span>）的动态平衡，以及<a href="/wuxing/">五行对应关系</a>（<span class="chinese-char">五行</span>）。在中医观念中，疾病并非有待消灭的入侵之敌，而是需要恢复的内在平衡失调。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="foundations">
      <h2>《黄帝内经》&mdash; 奠基之作</h2>
      <p>《<em>黄帝内经</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">黃帝內經</span>，Yellow Emperor's Classic of Internal Medicine）是中医学的奠基经典。成书于战国末期至西汉初年（约公元前300年 &ndash; 公元100年），以黄帝与其御医岐伯问答的形式撰写。</p>
      <p>全书分为两部分：《<em>素问</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">素問</span>，基础理论问答）论述医学原理，《<em>灵枢</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">靈樞</span>，针灸总论）详述针灸与经络理论。两者共同奠定了诊断原则、治疗策略与预防思想，至今仍为中医临床实践之核心。</p>
      <p>其他重要典籍包括：《<em>神农本草经</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">神農本草經</span>，约公元200年）收录365种药物，以及张仲景所著《<em>伤寒论</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">傷寒論</span>，约公元220年），后者堪称中医史上临床影响最为深远的方书。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="qi">
      <h2>气 &mdash; 生命之能</h2>
      <p>气（<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>）是中医最根本的概念。气指维系一切生命活动的vital能量，沿着称为<strong>经络</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">經絡</span>，jīngluò）的特定通路在体内循行。气行通畅、充盈则身体健康；气滞、气虚或气阻则百病丛生。</p>
      <p>中医区分数种气的类型：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>元气（<span class="chinese-char">元氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 先天之气，禀受于父母，藏于肾脏</li>
        <li><strong>谷气（<span class="chinese-char">穀氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 水谷之气，经脾胃运化饮食而生</li>
        <li><strong>宗气（<span class="chinese-char">宗氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 聚于胸中，由天气与谷气结合而成</li>
        <li><strong>卫气（<span class="chinese-char">衛氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 护卫之气，行于体表，抵御外邪</li>
        <li><strong>营气（<span class="chinese-char">營氣</span>）</strong> &mdash; 营养之气，行于经脉之中，濡养脏腑组织</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="zangfu">
      <h2>脏腑理论</h2>
      <p>中医依据<a href="/wuxing/">五行</a>对应关系，将人体内脏分为两组：</p>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>五行</th><th>脏（阴脏）</th><th>腑（阳腑）</th><th>情志</th><th>五官</th><th>主体</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>木</td><td>肝（<span class="chinese-char">肝</span>）</td><td>胆（<span class="chinese-char">膽</span>）</td><td>怒</td><td>目</td><td>筋</td></tr>
          <tr><td>火</td><td>心（<span class="chinese-char">心</span>）</td><td>小肠（<span class="chinese-char">小腸</span>）</td><td>喜</td><td>舌</td><td>脉</td></tr>
          <tr><td>土</td><td>脾（<span class="chinese-char">脾</span>）</td><td>胃（<span class="chinese-char">胃</span>）</td><td>思</td><td>口</td><td>肌肉</td></tr>
          <tr><td>金</td><td>肺（<span class="chinese-char">肺</span>）</td><td>大肠（<span class="chinese-char">大腸</span>）</td><td>悲</td><td>鼻</td><td>皮毛</td></tr>
          <tr><td>水</td><td>肾（<span class="chinese-char">腎</span>）</td><td>膀胱（<span class="chinese-char">膀胱</span>）</td><td>恐</td><td>耳</td><td>骨</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>必须理解，中医所言之脏腑乃<em>功能系统</em>，而非纯粹的解剖结构。例如中医之"脾"，涵盖消化运化与营养输布等功能 &mdash; 此等功能在西方医学中分属多个器官。五脏贮藏精微物质；六腑（包括三焦，<span class="chinese-char">三焦</span>）主转化输运。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="meridians">
      <h2>经络与针灸</h2>
      <p>经络系统（<span class="chinese-char">經絡</span>）由十二正经构成，连通内脏与体表，另有奇经八脉。经络之上分布着<strong>三百六十一个经典穴位</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">穴位</span>），各具特定治疗功效。</p>
      <p>针灸（<span class="chinese-char">針灸</span>，zhēnjiǔ）是在选定穴位施以细针，以调节气的运行、疏通阻滞、恢复阴阳平衡。《<em>灵枢</em>》详载补法（针对虚证）、泻法（针对实证）等针法技巧，以及影响气行方向与性质的各种手法。</p>
      <p>灸法（<span class="chinese-char">灸</span>，jiǔ）&mdash; 将干燥艾草（Artemisia vulgaris）置于穴位之上或附近燃烧 &mdash; 是针法的温热互补疗法，尤适用于寒证与虚证。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal">
      <h2>中药方剂</h2>
      <p>中药（<span class="chinese-char">中藥</span>，zhōngyào）是中医最广泛应用的分支。经典本草收录逾五千种药物 &mdash; 以植物为主，兼含矿物及动物类药材。药物依其性味分类：四气（热、温、凉、寒）、五味（酸、苦、甘、辛、咸），以及归经。</p>
      <p>方剂（<span class="chinese-char">方劑</span>）通常遵循严谨的组方逻辑配伍多味药材：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>君（<span class="chinese-char">君</span>）&mdash; 君药</strong>：针对主证的核心药物</li>
        <li><strong>臣（<span class="chinese-char">臣</span>）&mdash; 臣药</strong>：辅佐君药之功效</li>
        <li><strong>佐（<span class="chinese-char">佐</span>）&mdash; 佐药</strong>：兼治次要症状或缓和峻烈之性</li>
        <li><strong>使（<span class="chinese-char">使</span>）&mdash; 使药</strong>：引经报使或调和诸药</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal-medicine-detail">
      <h2>经典本草传统（<span class="chinese-char">中草藥</span>，<span class="pinyin">Zhōngcǎoyào</span>）</h2>
      <p>中草药学在<strong>明代</strong>巨著《<em>本草纲目</em>》（<span class="chinese-char">本草綱目</span>，<span class="pinyin">Běncǎo Gāngmù</span>）中达到了前近代的最高综合。此书由<strong>李时珍</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">李時珍</span>）历经二十七年研究，于1578年完成。全书收录<strong>一千八百九十二种药物</strong>，附方一万一千零九十六首，其分类体系之精密，已预示了现代分类学的思路。</p>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>李时珍亲尝众药，跋涉深山采集标本，并严谨审视历代医药文献。他订正了前人著述中的大量错误，摒弃迷信之说，其实证精神在当时的时代背景下实属非凡。</p>
        <cite>— 李时珍，<em>《本草纲目》</em>，明代（1578年）</cite>
      </div>
      <p>更早的里程碑著作包括：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><em>《神农本草经》</em></strong>（<span class="chinese-char">神農本草經</span>，约公元200年）— 第一部本草专著，将365种药物按毒性与疗效分为上、中、下三品</li>
        <li><strong><em>《伤寒论》</em></strong>（<span class="chinese-char">傷寒論</span>，约公元220年），张仲景著 — 外感热病的经方著作，至今仍广泛应用于临床</li>
        <li><strong><em>《千金要方》</em></strong>（<span class="chinese-char">千金要方</span>，652年），孙思邈（<span class="chinese-char">孫思邈</span>）著 — 唐代医学百科，融合中药、食疗与养生保健</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="food-therapy">
      <h2>食疗（<span class="chinese-char">食療</span>，<span class="pinyin">Shíliáo</span>）</h2>
      <p><strong>"药食同源"</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">藥食同源</span>，<span class="pinyin">yàoshí tóngyuán</span>）是中医学的根本理念。《<em>黄帝内经</em>》有云："治病先以食疗，食之不愈，然后用药。"食疗运用日常食材，依其性味（热、温、平、凉、寒）与味道分类，以防病养生、辅助康复。</p>

      <h3>广式食疗（<span class="chinese-char">廣式食療</span>）</h3>
      <p>广东发展出中国最为精致的食疗传统，此与岭南亚热带气候对清热祛湿食物的需求密不可分。<strong>广东老火汤</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">老火湯</span>，<span class="pinyin">lǎohuǒ tāng</span>）是最具代表性的食疗形式 — 以文火慢炖三至六小时，以充分萃取药材功效，常用材料包括：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">淮山</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">huáishān</span>，山药）— 健脾益气，补肾固精</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">蓮子</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">liánzǐ</span>，莲子）— 养心安神，涩肠止泻</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">杞子</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">qǐzǐ</span>，枸杞）— 滋补肝肾，明目益精</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">紅棗</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">hóngzǎo</span>，红枣）— 补中益气，养血调和</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">陳皮</span></strong>（<span class="pinyin">chénpí</span>，陈皮）— 理气燥湿，健脾助消化</li>
      </ul>
      <p>在广东家庭中，每日煲汤遵循时令逻辑：夏饮清热汤（<span class="chinese-char">清熱湯</span>），冬进温补汤（<span class="chinese-char">補湯</span>），春季潮湿回南天则煲祛湿汤。此乃文明尺度上的食疗实践。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="herbal-tea">
      <h2>广东凉茶（<span class="chinese-char">涼茶</span>，<span class="pinyin">Liángchá</span>）</h2>
      <p><strong>凉茶</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">涼茶</span>，字面意为"清凉之茶"）是广东地区以草药煎煮饮品来对抗炎热潮湿气候的传统。凉茶并非真正的茶叶（<em>Camellia sinensis</em>），而是带有药用功效的草本饮料，味道有时偏苦，用于日常保健。</p>
      <p>常见的凉茶配方包括：</p>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>名称</th><th>中文</th><th>主要药材</th><th>功效</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>王老吉</td><td><span class="chinese-char">王老吉</span></td><td>仙草、菊花、金银花</td><td>清热解毒，利咽消肿</td></tr>
          <tr><td>廿四味</td><td><span class="chinese-char">廿四味</span></td><td>二十四味药材（各店配方不同）</td><td>重度清热，解毒祛邪</td></tr>
          <tr><td>罗汉果茶</td><td><span class="chinese-char">羅漢果茶</span></td><td>罗汉果、菊花</td><td>止咳润肺</td></tr>
          <tr><td>鸡骨草茶</td><td><span class="chinese-char">雞骨草茶</span></td><td>鸡骨草、红枣</td><td>护肝利胆，清热祛湿</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>凉茶铺（<span class="chinese-char">涼茶鋪</span>）数百年来一直是广东街头的独特风景。2006年，凉茶文化被列入中国国家级非物质文化遗产名录，彰显其在岭南医药文化中的深厚根基。</p>
    </section>

    <section id="diagnosis">
      <h2>诊断方法</h2>
      <p>中医诊断依赖四诊合参（<span class="chinese-char">四診</span>）：</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>望诊（<span class="chinese-char">望</span>）</strong> &mdash; 观察面色、舌象、肤色、体型与神态。舌诊尤为精细，舌的颜色、苔质、形态与润燥皆反映体内状况。</li>
        <li><strong>闻诊（<span class="chinese-char">聞</span>）</strong> &mdash; 听辨声音、呼吸、咳嗽之质，嗅察体气</li>
        <li><strong>问诊（<span class="chinese-char">問</span>）</strong> &mdash; 系统询问症状、睡眠、食欲、消化、寒热偏向、情志状态及病史</li>
        <li><strong>切诊（<span class="chinese-char">切</span>）</strong> &mdash; 于寸口桡动脉处行脉诊，医者可辨二十八种脉象，分布三部九候，各对应不同脏腑系统</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="connection">
      <h2>中医与中国玄学</h2>
      <p>中医与中国玄学诸术共享相同的理论基因。用于医学诊断的<a href="/wuxing/">五行学说</a>，同样构成<a href="/bazi/">八字</a>命理分析、<a href="/fengshui/">风水</a>空间研判及<a href="/qimen/">奇门遁甲</a>时空预测的基本架构。<a href="/calendar/">中国历法</a>中的天干地支亦用于中医，以判断特定时间对人体健康的宇宙影响。</p>
      <p>此种互通并非偶然 &mdash; 它体现了中国宇宙观中"人身即天地之缩影"的核心思想，人体与自然界遵循同一法则。高明的医者诊察人体，恰如风水名家堪舆山川：皆在五行之间寻求和谐、通畅与平衡。</p>
    </section>
